arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase VII: Roman mid CE 2nd c. collapse and repairs. Aboveground canalization cut into the bedrock in the south and east. Installation of the low walls at the south ends of the East and West Walkways. Bench built along the south face of the South Corridor Wall. The floor of Room A is built up with purple sandstone bedding and low blocking wall. Room A is restructured as an animal shelter with tethering holes cut alongside the trough. Entrance to the Paradesios is blocked. A drain in the Forecourt is repaired and appointed with ceramic pipes for additional aboveground canalization.
1.20 m north south -by- 1.10 m east west.
Compact soil against the west of the small cistern

Locus 43 is the compact soil against the west face of the ‘small cistern’ and the ceramic channel, below Locus 1. The soil is extremely dense and immediately recognizable as different from the surrounding soil. It is a fine silt with a dark grayish brown color (Munsell 10 YR 4/2). There are large amounts of bones, pottery, and shell, with smaller quantities of metal and glass. This locus is very enigmatic, and though it is clearly bounded and very consistent in its inclusions, no easy explanation of it has been found. Below the floor level of the area, it could have been some sort of preparatory dumping for the ‘small cistern.’ It is so dense that small picks are required to loosen the soil, and presumably, being in an area full of water features (the ‘small cistern,’ the ceramic channel, and the vaulted channel) having a matrix such as this could almost be waterproof. The presence of the shells (mostly large conical snail shells), bones, and large storage vessels (including what looked like large platters) could suggest that this is evidence of cooking, but the lack of ash or burnt residue seems to prevent such an interpretation. Instead, Locus 43 should likely be seen as a dumping event, leveling the floor or otherwise preparing for the construction of the ‘small cistern’ or the floor. Most likely, when the ‘small cistern’ was added, the floor in the area would have had to be removed – Locus 43 can be seen as the subfloor leveling for the replacement of the floor. This would explain the localized area of the locus, with Locus 40 being the original subfloor leveling for the area, and Locus 44 (below both Locus 40 and Locus 43) being a lower soil level left intact when the ‘small cistern’ was constructed. This locus is phased to Stage 3 with the construction of the ‘small cistern.’
